15–":"1215–Deceased","1215–Female":"1215–Deceased","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1235–Male":"1235–Deceased","1215–Male":"1215–Deceased","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","about 1235":"about 1235","Abt 1225":"about 1225","Broadclyst, Devon, England":"Broadclyst, Devon, England","of Totnes, Devonshire, England":"Totnes, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Nonant","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon, of Norman origin): variant of   Conan  . Compare   Canant  .","History: Roger Conant led a secession from Plymouth colony <i>c.</i> 1627 and founded the settlement that became Salem, MA. He was probably the son of Christopher Connant, who came over from England aboard the <i>Anne</i> in 1623."],"variants":[{"name":"Canant","meanings":["Altered form of English   Conant  ."]},{"name":"Conan","meanings":["English and Scottish (of Breton origin): from the Old Breton personal name <i>Conan</i>, the name of Breton chiefs, kings, and of a saint, itself from British Celtic <i>Cunagnos</i>, a derivative of <i>cuno-</i> ‘hound’. This was one of the Breton names introduced to England at the Norman Conquest in 1066 and was common among tenants of the Richmond fee in Lincolnshire and Yorkshire. Compare   Conant  ."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Roger II de Nonant was born in 1215. He had at least 2 sons with Adelicia de Redvers."},"et":{"1215–":"1215–Surnud","1215–Female":"1215–Surnud","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1215–Male":"1215–Surnud","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","about 1235":"umbes 1235","Abt 1225":"umbes 1225","Broadclyst, Devon, England":"Broadclyst, Devon, England","of Totnes, Devonshire, England":"Totnes, Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1215–":"1215–Kuollut","1215–Female":"1215–Kuollut","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1215–Male":"1215–Kuollut","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","about 1235":"noin 1235","Abt 1225":"noin 1225","Broadclyst, Devon, England":"Broadclyst, Devon, England","of Totnes, Devonshire, England":"Totnes, Devon, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1215–":"1215–Décédé","1215–Female":"1215–Décédée","1225–Male":"1225–Décédé","1235–Male":"1235–Décédé","1215–Male":"1215–Décédé","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","about 1235":"environ 1235","Abt 1225":"environ 1225","Broadclyst, Devon, England":"Broadclyst, Devon, Angleterre","of Totnes, Devonshire, England":"Totnes, Devon, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Roger II de Nonant est né en 1215. Il a eu au moins 2 fils avec Adelicia de Redvers."},"de":{"1215–":"1215–Verstorben","1215–Female":"1215–Verstorben","1225–Male":"1225–Verstorben","1235–Male":"1235–Verstorben","1215–Male":"1215–Verstorben","1215":"1215","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","about 1235":"um 1235","Abt 1225":"um 1225","Broadclyst, Devon, England":"Broadclyst, Devon, England","of Totnes, Devonshire, England":"Totnes, Devon, England, United Kingdom","lifeSummary":"Roger II de Nonant wurde 1215 geboren. Er hatte mit Adelicia de Redvers mindestens 2 Söhne."},"ht":{"1215–":"1215–Desede","1215–Female":"1215–Desede","1225–Male":"1225–Desede","1235–Male":"1235–Desede","1215–Male":"1215–Desede","1215":"1215","1225":"1225